<TITLE> China urges firms to create more jobs in Africa </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, Aug 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Chinese firms investing in Africa should offer better pay and job opportunities, to counter concern that its competitive companies are damaging local economies, a vice commerce minister said on Tuesday. Wei Jianguo said that although African countries generally welcome Chinese investment, many were concerned that a flow of cheap goods into their domestic markets would hurt their fledgling industries. China is now the continent's third-largest trading partner, exporting $16.4 billion worth of goods and services in the first six months, up 49 percent from a year earlier. China's direct outbound investment in Africa reached $480 million in the first half of this year, the ministry said in a statement, without providing a comparison. But critics say that the trade is lopsided, with commodities flowing out of resource-rich but less-developed nations in return for a flow of cheap goods that have dented African manufacturing even though they please consumers. Earlier this summer a Ghanaian government minister warned that African nations should seek export markets in China and avoid a "colonial" relationship developing with Beijing as it buys up raw materials from the continent. With safety concerns about Chinese goods from toothpaste to toys mounting worldwide, Wei also urged Chinese firms to ensure their African ventures were producing good quality products and in an environmentally friendly way. But he warned that Chinese firms faced other challenges in Africa, particularly security. "These problems, if not solved in a timely fashion, will influence the long-term sustainable development of the China-Africa trade relationship," he add
